1
00:00:09,396 --> 00:00:10,396
Mommy!

2
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:12,363
- Guess what?
- What?

3
00:00:12,488 --> 00:00:15,483
Miss Mornie gave me a green ticket.
I got to go to the prize box.

4
00:00:15,608 --> 00:00:17,866
Prize box?
That's fantastic, Sophie.

5
00:00:18,304 --> 00:00:21,270
You know what I think?
Daddy would like to hear about this.

6
00:00:25,378 --> 00:00:27,457
It's Hardy.
I'm approaching the third floor.

7
00:00:27,582 --> 00:00:29,562
What unit was that disturbance call?

8
00:00:29,687 --> 00:00:30,691
<i>Unknown.</i>

9
00:00:30,816 --> 00:00:32,235
<i>Somewhere on floor 3.</i>

10
00:00:34,248 --> 00:00:36,048
Roger that.
I'll find it.

11
00:00:36,762 --> 00:00:39,657
Jimmy, I was supposed to be punched out
about 40 minutes ago.

12
00:00:39,782 --> 00:00:42,010
<i>Sorry, bro.
You caught the call.</i>

13
00:00:49,770 --> 00:00:50,919
What the hell you...

14
00:00:57,305 --> 00:01:00,220
<i>Hey, this is Nick.
You know what to do after the beep.</i>

15
00:01:00,884 --> 00:01:01,884
It's me.

16
00:01:03,642 --> 00:01:06,524
Guessing you're not going
to make it home for dinner again.

17
00:01:06,883 --> 00:01:08,734
Sophie really needs her father.

18
00:01:09,102 --> 00:01:11,604
When you get home,
we need to talk about this

19
00:01:11,729 --> 00:01:13,781
because something has to change.

20
00:01:39,133 --> 00:01:40,494
12.50 a share.

21
00:01:41,776 --> 00:01:43,144
It's the best I can do.

22
00:01:43,510 --> 00:01:46,772
If I'm going to pull the trigger,
it has to be at the right price, Don.

23
00:01:49,444 --> 00:01:51,277
Something tells me
you can do a lot better.

24
00:01:51,445 --> 00:01:52,835
I can't do better.

25
00:02:03,996 --> 00:02:05,710
I guess we're done here.

26
00:02:09,617 --> 00:02:11,839
You walk out of here now,
Don, and the deal's off.

27
00:02:12,267 --> 00:02:13,466
Are you sure

28
00:02:13,634 --> 00:02:15,342
there's no more money on the table?

29
00:02:18,515 --> 00:02:20,639
Fine. $13.

30
00:02:20,959 --> 00:02:22,141
Not a penny more.

31
00:02:22,309 --> 00:02:23,954
My absolute limit.

32
00:02:28,254 --> 00:02:30,149
Great.
We have a deal.

33
00:02:30,466 --> 00:02:31,776
You drive a hard bargain.

34
00:02:31,944 --> 00:02:34,111
And you have a private jet.
Seems fair.

35
00:02:41,631 --> 00:02:43,076
Not bad.
I pay you 10 grand,

36
00:02:43,201 --> 00:02:44,538
and you make me 15 million.

37
00:02:45,660 --> 00:02:48,042
Teach me.
The science, I mean.

38
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:49,227
You got 8 years?

39
00:02:49,352 --> 00:02:52,871
I want to shadow you, watch what you do.
How you do it. I'm a quick study.

40
00:02:53,304 --> 00:02:56,273
- I'll pay you 30 grand for the week.
- 50.

41
00:03:02,014 --> 00:03:05,016
- Get Loker down there with a camera.
- 40.

42
00:03:05,141 --> 00:03:06,448
A cop's been shot.

43
00:03:06,573 --> 00:03:08,270
I'm on retainer with the city.

44
00:03:09,980 --> 00:03:12,391
45. Take it or leave it.

45
00:03:15,435 --> 00:03:16,779
Why's the FBI on this?

46
00:03:16,904 --> 00:03:18,927
There was a shooting
on a federal housing project.

47
00:03:19,052 --> 00:03:21,742
There he is.
Captain James, D.C. police.

48
00:03:21,867 --> 00:03:24,301
Dr. Cal Lightman.
Given our present situation,

49
00:03:24,426 --> 00:03:26,636
- Lightman's the man.
- What's the situation?

50
00:03:26,761 --> 00:03:29,973
One of the bullets rendered
officer Nick Hardy a quadriplegic.

51
00:03:30,098 --> 00:03:33,337
He can't speak, can't move,
and we can't get a clear response

52
00:03:33,505 --> 00:03:35,276
to any of our questions.

53
00:03:35,401 --> 00:03:37,805
So you want me to help
identify the shooters.

54
00:03:39,081 --> 00:03:42,075
911 got a call from
the Eastmont projects.

55
00:03:42,514 --> 00:03:43,931
Tenants heard shots,

56
00:03:44,099 --> 00:03:47,017
and they saw two kids running
from the building in bloody shirts.

57
00:03:47,185 --> 00:03:50,271
They were caught a few blocks away,
but no shirts and no murder weapon.

58
00:03:51,075 --> 00:03:53,858
But residue
on one of their hands shows

59
00:03:54,026 --> 00:03:55,818
that he recently fired a gun.

60
00:03:55,986 --> 00:03:58,014
But without it,
we can't prove it was the gun.

61
00:03:58,139 --> 00:04:00,577
The surgeon says that Hardy
doesn't even have much time...

62
00:04:00,702 --> 00:04:03,284
Maybe a few days,
but more than likely, a few hours.

63
00:04:03,989 --> 00:04:05,578
Why are you so worried now?

64
00:04:05,746 --> 00:04:06,957
That's one of my men.

65
00:04:07,082 --> 00:04:09,109
You're concerned
you don't have the whole story yet.

66
00:04:09,234 --> 00:04:12,524
The kids that we picked up, they're just
runners for a small-time dealer.

67
00:04:12,649 --> 00:04:13,926
They never carried weapons,

68
00:04:14,051 --> 00:04:15,963
and they have no history
of violent crime.

69
00:04:16,131 --> 00:04:18,173
And then, one day,
they just shoot a cop.

70
00:04:18,341 --> 00:04:20,718
I think someone told them to gun up.

71
00:04:21,472 --> 00:04:22,928
But the question for you is,

72
00:04:23,053 --> 00:04:26,181
can you read a man
who can barely move his eyes?

73
00:04:28,977 --> 00:04:31,812
La <i><font color="#ff0000">Lie</font> <font color="#ffffff">to</font><font color="#ff0000"> team</font></i> présente:

74
00:04:56,671 --> 00:04:58,839
Episode 215: <i>Teacher and Pupils</i>

75
00:05:04,482 --> 00:05:05,668
Mrs. Hardy?

76
00:05:06,972 --> 00:05:07,973
Cal Lightman.

77
00:05:09,933 --> 00:05:10,942
You Sophie?

78
00:05:11,978 --> 00:05:12,978
How you doing?

79
00:05:16,729 --> 00:05:18,029
These are my colleagues.

80
00:05:18,154 --> 00:05:19,700
They told me you'd come.

81
00:05:23,922 --> 00:05:25,530
Mrs. Hardy,
maybe I can take you both

82
00:05:25,655 --> 00:05:28,202
to get something to drink
in the cafeteria.

83
00:05:34,360 --> 00:05:36,759
I love you.
We'll be right back.

84
00:05:39,497 --> 00:05:40,768
He liked that.

85
00:05:41,802 --> 00:05:43,772
Look at the muscles around the eyes.

86
00:05:44,972 --> 00:05:46,431
They contracted a bit.

87
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:48,347
It made him happier.

88
00:05:56,385 --> 00:05:59,164
While you're at it, Clara,
try and get ahold of Foster.

89
00:06:12,219 --> 00:06:13,219
Come on.

90
00:06:14,916 --> 00:06:18,073
Nick, I'm here to help find out
who did this to you.

91
00:06:18,461 --> 00:06:21,134
I know you can't answer questions
the way you normally would,

92
00:06:21,535 --> 00:06:23,549
but you just think it,

93
00:06:23,860 --> 00:06:26,385
and I'll try to do the rest, okay?

94
00:06:26,962 --> 00:06:30,097
I want to state for the record
that this show-up is beyond unorthodox.

95
00:06:30,347 --> 00:06:31,557
Shut up, counselor.

96
00:06:33,458 --> 00:06:34,971
You getting something?

97
00:06:36,912 --> 00:06:38,897
All right, Nick.
Are you 90 years old?

98
00:06:42,053 --> 00:06:43,591
Are you 30 years old?

99
00:06:48,659 --> 00:06:49,659
There.

100
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:52,737
Right there.
His pupils.

101
00:06:54,875 --> 00:06:56,672
Can you bring those two over?

102
00:06:57,891 --> 00:06:59,250
And lean them right in.

103
00:07:01,463 --> 00:07:04,506
I know you're tired, but I need you
to concentrate, all right?

104
00:07:05,137 --> 00:07:06,467
Were these two boys there

105
00:07:06,635 --> 00:07:07,968
when you were shot?

106
00:07:10,471 --> 00:07:13,307
It's a positive affirmation.
That's a "yes" to you, counselor.

107
00:07:14,623 --> 00:07:15,642
One at a time.

108
00:07:18,723 --> 00:07:20,230
Did this one shoot you?

109
00:07:23,818 --> 00:07:24,818
Nothing?

110
00:07:26,470 --> 00:07:27,584
And the other?

111
00:07:28,669 --> 00:07:29,896
In he comes now.

112
00:07:32,285 --> 00:07:33,660
Did this one shoot you?

113
00:07:36,457 --> 00:07:37,581
There it is.

114
00:07:39,918 --> 00:07:42,169
They were both there
when he was shot,

115
00:07:42,337 --> 00:07:44,630
but this one, he pulled the trigger.

116
00:07:44,798 --> 00:07:46,757
What's your next trick,
reading tea leaves?

117
00:07:46,882 --> 00:07:50,257
This is all total garbage. I'm giving
my clients back to social services

118
00:07:50,470 --> 00:07:52,096
- and back to county.
- No.

119
00:07:53,981 --> 00:07:55,766
We know you were working
with someone.

120
00:07:56,288 --> 00:07:57,518
If you fess up now,

121
00:07:57,686 --> 00:07:59,394
we can protect you from that person.

122
00:08:00,321 --> 00:08:02,564
Look at that...
honest fear, it is.

123
00:08:02,732 --> 00:08:04,566
Dont say anything.
There are no questions.

124
00:08:04,734 --> 00:08:06,308
Right against self-incrimination.

125
00:08:06,433 --> 00:08:09,183
They also have a right
to self-preservation.

126
00:08:09,692 --> 00:08:12,094
They cooperate,
maybe we can cut a deal,

127
00:08:12,219 --> 00:08:15,118
because we are going to find
who you were working for.

128
00:08:15,802 --> 00:08:18,664
- We were doing a job for...
- You don't have to say anything.

129
00:08:18,832 --> 00:08:21,792
We were slanging drugs for Tevon,
and this cop creeped up on us.

130
00:08:23,025 --> 00:08:24,422
In our neighborhood,

131
00:08:25,244 --> 00:08:26,849
someone comes up behind you,

132
00:08:26,974 --> 00:08:28,715
you don't ask questions.
You shoot.

133
00:08:31,998 --> 00:08:34,655
Went down before we even knew
he was the police.

134
00:08:37,245 --> 00:08:39,893
He's lying.
Clara, how do I know he's lying?

135
00:08:40,061 --> 00:08:41,687
For 45 grand, why don't you tell me?

136
00:08:43,482 --> 00:08:44,506
Here we go.

137
00:08:45,524 --> 00:08:47,609
<i>Went down before we even knew
he was the police.</i>

138
00:08:49,027 --> 00:08:50,898
There.
Duping-delight.

139
00:08:51,225 --> 00:08:53,392
Some people can't help
the tiniest hint of a smile

140
00:08:53,517 --> 00:08:55,619
when they think they've
gotten away with a lie.

141
00:08:55,744 --> 00:08:58,060
- Who's Tevon?
- Their language is all past tense.

142
00:08:58,185 --> 00:09:00,723
It's like they're unconsciously
cutting ties from this person.

143
00:09:00,848 --> 00:09:02,332
He's the dealer.

144
00:09:02,500 --> 00:09:04,623
He runs the projects.
Real scumbag.

145
00:09:04,748 --> 00:09:07,479
May have been running drugs for him,
but that's not who they were working for

146
00:09:07,604 --> 00:09:09,631
- when they bumped into Hardy.
- Sure?

147
00:09:09,862 --> 00:09:11,731
Sure as the lie on his face.

148
00:09:11,856 --> 00:09:14,272
Whoever they were working for
scares them enough

149
00:09:14,397 --> 00:09:17,749
- they would rather serve up Tevon.
- Or maybe there's a rival dealer

150
00:09:17,874 --> 00:09:19,933
trying to recruit
some of Tevon's runners.

151
00:09:20,166 --> 00:09:22,861
- We should go talk to him.
- That's not who they were working for.

152
00:09:22,986 --> 00:09:24,271
Why do you want see him?

153
00:09:24,439 --> 00:09:27,983
- The first rule of policeman...
- Stop for coffee?

154
00:09:28,501 --> 00:09:29,847
Follow every lead.

155
00:09:34,801 --> 00:09:37,284
We need to talk.
Maybe alone.

156
00:09:38,167 --> 00:09:41,121
I'll just go get a snack
while you two talk about Clara.

157
00:09:41,289 --> 00:09:43,841
Good grief. Sit down.
What about Clara?

158
00:09:43,966 --> 00:09:46,210
Our accountant says we can't
make payroll next week.

159
00:09:46,378 --> 00:09:48,909
- Terrific. Start the layoffs, then.
- The situation is serious.

160
00:09:49,034 --> 00:09:51,250
Keeping your daughter
is not going to keep me from yelling

161
00:09:51,375 --> 00:09:53,840
- until I get through to you.
- All right, calm down.

162
00:09:53,965 --> 00:09:56,303
What about Clara...
Formally, Mrs. Bailout?

163
00:09:56,471 --> 00:10:00,114
Maybe she's more valuable
than just a one-day ridealong.

164
00:10:00,239 --> 00:10:01,626
Let me get this straight.

165
00:10:01,751 --> 00:10:05,736
You're asking me
to ask Clara for a loan?

166
00:10:05,861 --> 00:10:08,941
She could know people...
with money who could use our services...

167
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:11,141
She's our client.
I don't ask clients for loans.

168
00:10:11,266 --> 00:10:13,445
- I don't mix business with pleasure.
- Pleasure?

169
00:10:17,680 --> 00:10:20,494
If you want to discuss some
kind of business deal, I'm open to it.

170
00:10:20,662 --> 00:10:22,411
That's much appreciated,

171
00:10:23,231 --> 00:10:24,748
but, your money's no good here.

172
00:10:25,703 --> 00:10:27,994
This would probably be
a bad time to ask

173
00:10:28,119 --> 00:10:30,337
for the $300 I need for the dance.

174
00:10:30,505 --> 00:10:32,599
Since when does it cost
$300 to dance?

175
00:10:32,724 --> 00:10:35,092
I need a new dress, shoes...

176
00:10:35,368 --> 00:10:36,805
Hair, manicure.

177
00:10:37,977 --> 00:10:39,972
Clearly outnumbered here.

178
00:10:43,057 --> 00:10:43,892
There.

179
00:10:44,184 --> 00:10:45,602
- Thank you.
- I want receipts.

180
00:10:47,844 --> 00:10:50,774
I just keep coming to you
with this problem, you keep ignoring it.

181
00:10:51,164 --> 00:10:52,484
Find a loan, then.

182
00:10:52,712 --> 00:10:55,045
I know some money men.
I could help you with this.

183
00:10:55,170 --> 00:10:56,029
Ready?

184
00:11:02,763 --> 00:11:04,773
You don't think
you're coming along, do you?

185
00:11:04,898 --> 00:11:06,901
- Absolutely.
- No, she's my colleague.

186
00:11:07,083 --> 00:11:08,472
Wherever I go, she goes.

187
00:11:09,132 --> 00:11:10,871
Fine, but she's signing a waiver.

188
00:11:12,169 --> 00:11:15,368
I tell you what, why don't you go with
Foster and sign the necessary papers?

189
00:11:15,755 --> 00:11:18,445
While you're at it, you can give her
the names of those money men.

190
00:11:18,570 --> 00:11:20,679
- Glad to help.
- To the right.

191
00:11:21,494 --> 00:11:23,187
Let's go before she comes back now.

192
00:11:25,774 --> 00:11:28,747
Tevon moves around the projects
every few months.

193
00:11:29,009 --> 00:11:31,696
Makes it harder for the UCS
to keep a bead on him.

194
00:11:32,118 --> 00:11:34,668
Our intel says
he's on the fourth floor.

195
00:11:35,153 --> 00:11:36,903
But we don't know which apartment.

196
00:11:41,397 --> 00:11:43,452
We're the cops.
Who wants to be strip-searched?

197
00:11:51,911 --> 00:11:54,796
There's your apartment.
It's the first one down on the left.

198
00:11:55,716 --> 00:11:57,841
- How do you know?
- If you put a drop of water

199
00:11:58,009 --> 00:12:00,441
in front of ants, they'll avoid it
they think it's dangerous.

200
00:12:00,566 --> 00:12:03,096
The kids did the same.
They steered clear of that apartment.

201
00:12:03,264 --> 00:12:06,014
- Probably for the same reason.
- All right.

202
00:12:07,745 --> 00:12:09,936
You're a civilian.
You stay in the stairwell.

203
00:12:11,505 --> 00:12:13,732
Can I have a badge and a gun?
Can you deputize me?

204
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:15,127
Yeah, nice try.

205
00:12:15,252 --> 00:12:17,986
Listen, you get in any trouble,
you call us.

206
00:12:18,425 --> 00:12:20,129
All right.
Thank you very much.

207
00:12:24,213 --> 00:12:26,328
I walked this beat 20 years.

208
00:12:26,890 --> 00:12:28,590
Pretty tough, all right?

209
00:12:37,012 --> 00:12:39,383
- Yeah?
- Police. Tevon in?

210
00:12:39,551 --> 00:12:42,761
- No. Tevon ain't here.
- I guess we just have to wait for him.

211
00:12:43,516 --> 00:12:46,848
- Yo, man, drop it!
- Drop the gun. We're cops.

212
00:12:47,016 --> 00:12:49,559
Man, I got shot by a guy
saying they was cops before.

213
00:12:49,727 --> 00:12:52,071
I ain't going for it then,
I ain't going for it now.

214
00:12:52,196 --> 00:12:54,713
So y'all drop the gun,
or I'm pulling the trigger.

215
00:13:00,691 --> 00:13:02,697
Son, you are playing this all wrong.

216
00:13:02,865 --> 00:13:05,871
What's wrong is y'all creepin' round
my door trying to cap me, man.

217
00:13:05,996 --> 00:13:08,954
<i>Captain James, this is officer Lightman.
We got SWAT outside.</i>

218
00:13:09,122 --> 00:13:11,638
<i>The sniper has the subject in sight
through the south window.</i>

219
00:13:11,994 --> 00:13:14,498
Good. I hope they shoot your ass
in the back of the head.

220
00:13:14,623 --> 00:13:15,613
Shut up, bitch!

221
00:13:15,738 --> 00:13:18,135
<i>Officer James, please respond.
Do we greenlight the sniper?</i>

222
00:13:18,260 --> 00:13:21,763
Let me tell you something. Those snipers
are going to put a bullet in your brain

223
00:13:21,888 --> 00:13:23,848
unless you drop that gun right now.

224
00:13:23,973 --> 00:13:26,430
You have 3 seconds.
Put the gun down.

225
00:13:26,598 --> 00:13:27,931
Put it down.

226
00:13:29,198 --> 00:13:30,198
1...

227
00:13:31,141 --> 00:13:32,687
- 2...
- All right, yo.

228
00:13:33,474 --> 00:13:35,237
Ain't knew
y'all was really cops, man.

229
00:13:35,362 --> 00:13:38,483
Thought y'all was here to mess
with my business. All right. Cool.

230
00:13:38,651 --> 00:13:39,651
Put it down.

231
00:13:39,819 --> 00:13:41,589
Easy, man. Cool.

232
00:13:44,253 --> 00:13:46,658
Hey, man. Look.
All this is just one big honest mistake.

233
00:13:46,826 --> 00:13:48,785
I know it was.
So was this.

234
00:13:50,472 --> 00:13:52,414
- Come on, man.
- Take a walk, honey.

235
00:13:54,700 --> 00:13:55,700
Hey, man!

236
00:13:57,629 --> 00:13:59,033
Man, this ain't justice.

237
00:13:59,661 --> 00:14:02,549
- What this is about?
- Who's your deputy now, then?

238
00:14:05,043 --> 00:14:07,400
Yo, man, those kids
are straight-up liars.

239
00:14:07,525 --> 00:14:09,636
All I told them to do
was run product,

240
00:14:09,761 --> 00:14:11,519
and by product, I mean chewing gum.

241
00:14:12,118 --> 00:14:14,833
He's telling the truth,
except for the gum part.

242
00:14:14,958 --> 00:14:16,834
See, man?
Listen to him.

243
