00:29:16,251 --> 00:29:18,214
I've spent a fortune and
not looked half as good.

491
00:29:18,382 --> 00:29:19,382
Thank you.

492
00:29:22,055 --> 00:29:25,055
- Have fun with your client.
- You have fun, too.

493
00:29:25,240 --> 00:29:27,335
The equity fund manager's waiting.

494
00:29:27,460 --> 00:29:28,935
We're going to be late.

495
00:29:29,060 --> 00:29:31,710
Good luck.
You can fill me in over dinner.

496
00:29:33,402 --> 00:29:35,398
So to speak.
Or not.

497
00:29:36,164 --> 00:29:37,214
Focus. Hmm?

498
00:29:41,743 --> 00:29:45,154
Right. John and George, right?
Talking about their new secretary.

499
00:29:45,279 --> 00:29:47,323
And John says,
"I took her out last night,

500
00:29:47,448 --> 00:29:49,199
"and we went at it all night.

501
00:29:49,324 --> 00:29:50,955
Yeah, she's better than my wife."

502
00:29:51,123 --> 00:29:53,128
So the next day, George comes in.
He says,

503
00:29:53,253 --> 00:29:56,624
"I took her out last night.
"We went at it all night.

504
00:29:57,289 --> 00:30:00,839
I think you're right.
I think she is better than your wife."

505
00:30:04,070 --> 00:30:05,761
Right. Well, you're the boss,

506
00:30:05,929 --> 00:30:07,680
'cause everyone else, they waited

507
00:30:07,848 --> 00:30:10,074
just a millisecond
before they laughed.

508
00:30:10,199 --> 00:30:12,476
You, you laughed, but
you found it offensive.

509
00:30:12,644 --> 00:30:14,446
Being the family man that you are.

510
00:30:14,571 --> 00:30:16,389
You, you got turned on by it.

511
00:30:16,514 --> 00:30:17,514
And you...

512
00:30:18,170 --> 00:30:21,118
well, you'd heard it before,
but you laughed anyway.

513
00:30:21,243 --> 00:30:22,943
Your laugh was fake. So.

514
00:30:24,102 --> 00:30:26,365
That's what we do, gentlemen.
We read people.

515
00:30:26,533 --> 00:30:28,200
If you're lying or cheating,

516
00:30:28,512 --> 00:30:31,495
your face will let us know before
anything you're saying ever does.

517
00:30:33,206 --> 00:30:35,207
Well, I look forward
to working with you.

518
00:30:43,056 --> 00:30:45,384
Well, you sure know how to
show a girl a good time.

519
00:30:46,343 --> 00:30:48,443
Well, it's been a while, has it?

520
00:30:48,698 --> 00:30:51,698
You know, everyone needs
a reminder now and then.

521
00:30:52,100 --> 00:30:54,560
So, what's this really
all about, Clara?

522
00:30:55,179 --> 00:30:56,880
- I don't follow.
- That's 'cause

523
00:30:57,064 --> 00:30:59,064
you've been too busy trying
to lead, haven't you?

524
00:30:59,547 --> 00:31:02,186
Mmm. I paid good money
for that privilege.

525
00:31:02,311 --> 00:31:04,221
Doing you a favor.
45 grand?

526
00:31:04,346 --> 00:31:06,805
That's chump change for
someone like you, isn't it?

527
00:31:06,930 --> 00:31:10,075
If you were interested in what I do,
you'd have made a play for me by now.

528
00:31:10,718 --> 00:31:14,538
Well, no. I mean, not play for me.
A play for firm.

529
00:31:15,408 --> 00:31:17,124
Over your dead body.

530
00:31:18,789 --> 00:31:20,260
What's your game, Cal?

531
00:31:25,753 --> 00:31:26,759
Hello, Em.

532
00:31:28,139 --> 00:31:29,762
What?
Now, say that again.

533
00:31:30,771 --> 00:31:33,349
All right.
You say nothing until I get there.

534
00:31:34,259 --> 00:31:35,509
You understand?

535
00:31:35,637 --> 00:31:37,144
- Nothing.
- What's wrong?

536
00:31:37,568 --> 00:31:41,218
You take the car. The bastards
arrested my daughter for drugs.

537
00:31:55,405 --> 00:31:59,409
- Cal Lightman. Where's my daughter?
- Mr. Lightman, let's talk in here.

538
00:32:00,475 --> 00:32:02,661
Where's my daughter, officer?

539
00:32:03,216 --> 00:32:06,094
I can understand your
concern, also being a dad.

540
00:32:06,219 --> 00:32:07,819
These kids today, huh?

541
00:32:08,891 --> 00:32:10,591
Yeah. So, where is she?

542
00:32:10,762 --> 00:32:12,813
Take a breath.
It's OK. She's coming.

543
00:32:12,938 --> 00:32:15,203
Seriously, take a breath, pal.

544
00:32:17,146 --> 00:32:19,246
Well, see, I just want her back.

545
00:32:20,845 --> 00:32:24,441
- You're going to let her go.
- You seem like a smart guy, doting dad.

546
00:32:24,761 --> 00:32:27,528
We all make mistakes.
Correct?

547
00:32:30,406 --> 00:32:32,556
There a reason not to let her go?

548
00:32:33,725 --> 00:32:35,684
Oh, no.
Can't think of one.

549
00:32:35,809 --> 00:32:36,704
All right.

550
00:32:43,516 --> 00:32:44,628
Well, thank you.

551
00:32:45,572 --> 00:32:46,922
Don't mention it.

552
00:32:48,896 --> 00:32:49,967
That's it, then?

553
00:32:50,135 --> 00:32:51,885
You tell me if that's it.

554
00:32:55,807 --> 00:32:57,391
I think we understand each other.

555
00:32:57,859 --> 00:32:59,476
Oh, yeah. Yeah. Yeah.

556
00:33:01,628 --> 00:33:02,928
Here she is now.

557
00:33:04,819 --> 00:33:06,883
Dad! I didn't do anything. I swear.

558
00:33:07,008 --> 00:33:09,387
I know that, love.
I absolutely, sweetie.

559
00:33:09,512 --> 00:33:12,624
Count yourself lucky, Emily.
Most kids around here don't get bail

560
00:33:12,749 --> 00:33:16,753
when they're caught with enough cocaine
for an "intent to distribute."

561
00:33:17,913 --> 00:33:20,403
Come on. Let's go.
Come on.

562
00:33:32,138 --> 00:33:35,746
I want to officially notify you that
this is now an FBI investigation.

563
00:33:36,548 --> 00:33:37,556
Wait a minute.

564
00:33:38,060 --> 00:33:40,831
<i>I came down here because you told me
you were looking for</i>

565
00:33:40,956 --> 00:33:42,628
<i>a new focus in the investigation.</i>

566
00:33:42,966 --> 00:33:46,763
<i>The new focus is the relationship
between you and your boy Hollander.</i>

567
00:33:47,263 --> 00:33:50,069
<i>I told you I'd take care of Hollander
and his men.</i>

568
00:33:50,780 --> 00:33:52,946
He crossed a line.
That was my daughter.

569
00:33:53,114 --> 00:33:55,199
- And I'm sorry.
- That better be genuine

570
00:33:55,367 --> 00:33:57,929
concern for my Emily, 'cause
my blood is well up,

571
00:33:58,054 --> 00:34:00,289
my judgment is way out of whack,
so keep talking.

572
00:34:00,414 --> 00:34:02,915
- Those men were out of line.
- The other night,

573
00:34:03,040 --> 00:34:04,935
you lied about the reasons
for your guilt.

574
00:34:05,060 --> 00:34:07,544
You are to blame for Hardy's death,
but not because you sent him

575
00:34:07,712 --> 00:34:10,327
off to the projects, but because
you're up to your eyes in this

576
00:34:10,570 --> 00:34:12,967
with Hollander and his thugs.
Or should I say your thugs?

577
00:34:13,092 --> 00:34:15,965
- And that wasn't a bloody question.
- This is more complicated.

578
00:34:16,090 --> 00:34:17,195
Why?

579
00:34:18,209 --> 00:34:21,558
Whose side are you on, James?
'Cause on the one hand, you grieve

580
00:34:21,726 --> 00:34:23,740
for Hardy's death, right?

581
00:34:23,988 --> 00:34:26,745
But somehow, you're involved
with the men responsible for it. So...

582
00:34:26,870 --> 00:34:28,023
He was a good man.

583
00:34:28,191 --> 00:34:30,860
Why don't you save the B.S.
For his widow and answer the question?

584
00:34:30,985 --> 00:34:33,487
You guys think that
I'm running a crew of dirty cops?

585
00:34:33,655 --> 00:34:35,155
I don't think it.
I see it.

586
00:34:35,323 --> 00:34:37,699
- Why are you protecting them?
- I'm not protecting them.

587
00:34:37,824 --> 00:34:40,531
No, you're protecting yourself.
I'm coming at you, James,

588
00:34:40,758 --> 00:34:42,955
with everything I've got,
and you know that?

589
00:34:43,174 --> 00:34:45,989
Not just because of my daughter,
but because of Hardy's wife and kid.

590
00:34:46,263 --> 00:34:47,543
You do remember them?

591
00:34:49,131 --> 00:34:51,541
A lot of people in those projects
are good people,

592
00:34:51,666 --> 00:34:53,314
just trying to live their lives.

593
00:34:53,531 --> 00:34:57,066
Which is hard enough without dealers
and pimps and scumbags.

594
00:34:57,812 --> 00:35:00,180
Well, I smell police vigilantism.

595
00:35:00,510 --> 00:35:03,434
The people in that building
called it safety.

596
00:35:04,693 --> 00:35:06,758
You don't have to see what we see,

597
00:35:06,883 --> 00:35:08,856
day after day, year after year.

598
00:35:10,942 --> 00:35:14,403
4 years ago, I pulled a baby
out of a dumpster for the last time.

599
00:35:15,658 --> 00:35:18,620
That's when I had Hollander
and his crew set an example

600
00:35:19,226 --> 00:35:21,312
of a couple of the problem tenants,

601
00:35:21,880 --> 00:35:23,815
so the rest of the trash would know

602
00:35:23,940 --> 00:35:26,248
that they were not tolerated
in my projects.

603
00:35:26,714 --> 00:35:28,250
- Your projects?
- My projects!

604
00:35:29,497 --> 00:35:31,003
Somebody's got to own them.

605
00:35:31,711 --> 00:35:35,181
If we just did things by the book,
which doesn't exist, anyway,

606
00:35:35,306 --> 00:35:36,633
nothing would get done.

607
00:35:38,857 --> 00:35:40,900
I swear on my mother's grave,

608
00:35:41,212 --> 00:35:43,894
I didn't know Hollander was running
a rent scam,

609
00:35:44,019 --> 00:35:46,059
and I didn't know anything
about any killings.

610
00:35:46,227 --> 00:35:48,771
So, you really believed
that you were doing good there.

611
00:35:48,939 --> 00:35:50,147
I know I was.

612
00:35:50,797 --> 00:35:52,883
You can't be that naive.

613
00:35:54,851 --> 00:35:55,851
Naive?

614
00:35:56,267 --> 00:35:57,392
No. Arrogant.

615
00:35:58,213 --> 00:36:01,784
Arrogant enough to believe that
my men would never let me down.

616
00:36:01,952 --> 00:36:02,952
Yeah, well,

617
00:36:03,545 --> 00:36:04,545
they did.

618
00:36:05,016 --> 00:36:07,748
So you're going to help us end this,
if it's the last thing you do.

619
00:36:08,522 --> 00:36:11,794
You're going to go pick up Hollander
and bring him back here.

620
00:36:12,954 --> 00:36:14,671
We'll grab the other turd.

621
00:36:23,548 --> 00:36:24,598
Officer Tressler,

622
00:36:25,115 --> 00:36:26,809
FBI.
You're under arrest.

623
00:36:26,977 --> 00:36:29,899
You can't just arrest an officer
of the law 'cause you feel like it.

624
00:36:30,024 --> 00:36:31,791
Come on. Let's go.
Let's go.

625
00:36:33,175 --> 00:36:35,207
Now you know how my daughter felt.

626
00:36:43,643 --> 00:36:44,724
There he is.

627
00:36:46,478 --> 00:36:47,916
I'm glad you could come.

628
00:36:48,207 --> 00:36:49,289
What's the matter?

629
00:36:49,457 --> 00:36:50,867
Did I strike a nerve?

630
00:36:51,624 --> 00:36:54,545
What, don't you like being yanked out
of your life to be here with me?

631
00:36:54,713 --> 00:36:56,547
You got nothing on me.
This is bull.

632
00:36:56,672 --> 00:36:58,757
- How's your daughter doin'?
- She's doing fine.

633
00:36:58,925 --> 00:37:00,384
Grades have dropped a bit.

634
00:37:00,552 --> 00:37:02,428
The boys have already
started talking.

635
00:37:02,553 --> 00:37:04,763
We've just got a couple
of quick questions for you.

636
00:37:25,746 --> 00:37:28,846
You have no right to keep us here.
Get me a lawyer.

637
00:37:29,192 --> 00:37:31,582
People who show genuine guilt
and remorse are more

638
00:37:31,750 --> 00:37:34,167
- likely to confess.
- You read that on which one?

639
00:37:34,335 --> 00:37:36,920
Tressler. At the police station,
Lightman read that he wasn't

640
00:37:37,088 --> 00:37:39,297
comfortable with what his partners
did to Emily.

641
00:37:39,422 --> 00:37:43,343
If a member of a group feels that the
group has strayed from its moral code,

642
00:37:43,699 --> 00:37:45,596
that member's
discomfort manifests itself

643
00:37:45,764 --> 00:37:48,891
in physical distancing from the group,
micro-expressions

644
00:37:49,059 --> 00:37:51,184
of disagreement.
And Lightman said that this guy

645
00:37:51,352 --> 00:37:53,421
was showing all of those
at the precinct.

646
00:37:53,546 --> 00:37:56,273
He's doing it right now.
He's on the opposite side of him.

647
00:38:02,956 --> 00:38:05,983
<i>How you doing? You know what?
He's the worst kind of cop,</i>

648
00:38:06,512 --> 00:38:08,619
- <i>don't you think?</i>
- <i>He's a good cop.</i>

649
00:38:09,118 --> 00:38:11,622
His voice trailed off.
He doesn't believe that.

650
00:38:11,929 --> 00:38:13,832
<i>I'm sorry.
Could you say that again?</i>

651
00:38:14,245 --> 00:38:16,126
It's mind games.
It's all mind games.

652
00:38:16,580 --> 00:38:17,586
You can go.

653
00:38:18,461 --> 00:38:19,713
We don't need you anymore.

654
00:38:20,137 --> 00:38:22,170
<i>We've got him.
Seriously, off you go.</i>

655
00:38:25,023 --> 00:38:26,483
What, you scared, are you?

656
00:38:27,772 --> 00:38:30,015
You scared to leave
without your boyfriend here?

657
00:38:31,869 --> 00:38:34,603
- I think I want a lawyer.
- He used the word "think."

658
00:38:34,771 --> 00:38:37,064
He's equivocating.
He wants to unburden himself.

659
00:38:37,189 --> 00:38:39,656
<i>I think I know
what Captain James was doing,</i>

660
00:38:39,781 --> 00:38:41,721
<i>or thought he was doing,</i>
in those projects.

661
00:38:42,314 --> 00:38:44,044
He was taking out trash, right?

662
00:38:44,736 --> 00:38:45,784
Look at you.

663
00:38:46,157 --> 00:38:47,384
That's pride, that is.

664
00:38:48,528 --> 00:38:49,782
He's puffed up

665
00:38:50,225 --> 00:38:51,286
like a peacock.

666
00:38:51,615 --> 00:38:53,205
- Lawyer.
- That's fair enough.

667
00:38:53,373 --> 00:38:54,787
You can have a lawyer.

668
00:38:54,912 --> 00:38:57,042
I'm not asking you to say anything.

669
00:38:58,229 --> 00:39:00,963
Not verbally, anyway. His face
has already told me you killed Hardy.

670
00:39:01,224 --> 00:39:02,673
That's a lie.
I did not!

671
00:39:03,083 --> 00:39:05,509
No, I'm sorry.
I mean had him killed. Had him killed.

672
00:39:06,080 --> 00:39:07,702
<i>Had him killed.
That's it. Right.</i>

673
00:39:08,685 --> 00:39:09,721
<i>Those kids...</i>

674
00:39:11,841 --> 00:39:13,267
It was an accident.

675
00:39:13,947 --> 00:39:17,062
- Now we're getting somewhere.
- OK. We're through here. Let's go.

676
00:39:17,612 --> 00:39:20,273
- Here we go.
- You know, you left Hardy,

677
00:39:20,672 --> 00:39:21,699
<i>a father</i>

678
00:39:22,628 --> 00:39:25,112
<i>and a husband,</i> to bleed out alone.

679
00:39:27,148 --> 00:39:28,907
He's gonna do you next,
you know that?

680
00:39:29,075 --> 00:39:30,784
Shut up.
That's enough.

681
00:39:31,624 --> 00:39:32,703
Make me.

682
00:39:33,721 --> 00:39:35,706
Go on. Make me.

683
00:39:36,916 --> 00:39:38,500
No. I want you to...

684
00:39:38,668 --> 00:39:39,668
make me.

685
00:39:42,019 --> 00:39:44,300
- Then you went after my daughter.
- No.

686
00:39:44,549 --> 00:39:47,079
No? Well, his Adam's apple says yes.
You know, look at it.

687
00:39:47,442 --> 00:39:48,885
It's like a cork in a storm.

688
00:39:49,626 --> 00:39:51,763
And you see that look?
That's very common

689
00:39:51,888 --> 00:39:53,745
on people with intent
to commit murder.

690
00:39:54,383 --> 00:39:55,383
16,

691
00:39:55,756 --> 00:39:56,783
my daughter.

692
00:39:57,347 --> 00:39:58,353
She's 16.

693
00:39:58,883 --> 00:40:01,648
Some man you are. Don't look at him.
He can't help you.

694
00:40:04,437 --> 00:40:05,610
I didn't want to.

695
00:40:05,778 --> 00:40:08,539
- <i>You didn't want to what?</i>
- <i>What, threaten my family?</i>

696
00:40:08,664 --> 00:40:11,283
<i>No, but you did, though.
You went along with it.</i>

697
00:40:11,759 --> 00:40:14,359
- 'Cause you're scared of him.
- I'm not.

698
00:40:15,262 --> 00:40:16,912
- Coffee break?
- Yes.

699
00:40:23,802 --> 00:40:24,802
Wait.

700
00:40:25,251 --> 00:40:27,591
I only knew about the two boys
killing Jenkins.

701
00:40:31,445 --> 00:40:32,554
<i>Excuse me?</i>

702
00:40:33,134 --> 00:40:35,134
We saw Hardy lying there,
bleeding out.

703
00:40:35,448 --> 00:40:37,290
But Jenkins was already dead.

704
00:40:37,415 --> 00:40:39,772
- His apartment door was wide open.
- That's enough.

705
00:40:39,897 --> 00:40:41,772
We closed it,
and we moved the body later.

706
00:40:42,363 --> 00:40:43,565
You killed Jenkins

707
00:40:43,733 --> 00:40:45,525
to shut him up about your rent scam.

708
00:40:45,948 --> 00:40:47,040
That's it.

709
00:40:47,165 --> 00:40:48,862
I just wanted to make
a few extra bucks,

710
00:40:49,177 --> 00:40:51,329
and then,
this Jenkins guy starts causing trouble.

711
00:40:51,454 --> 00:40:53,575
Shut up.
You're smarter than this. Come on.

712
00:40:53,743 --> 00:40:55,660
And next thing I know,
Hollander tells me

713
00:40:55,828 --> 00:40:58,038
that he's dead,
and we have to move the body.

714
00:41:06,274 --> 00:41:07,923
Prison's too good for you, mate.

715
00:41:08,544 --> 00:41:10,008
But I suppose it will have to do.

716
00:41:11,708 --> 00:41:13,308
I've made a couple of calls.

717
00:41:14,119 --> 00:41:15,762
I've let them know you're coming.

718
00:41:21,905 --> 00:41:23,408
I said 45 grand, by the way.

719
00:41:23,533 --> 00:41:26,154
Consider it a discount
for ditching me.

720
00:41:28,727 --> 00:41:30,835
So, Captain James will cut a deal,

721
00:41:30,960 --> 00:41:33,216
but the rest of 'em are looking
at a life sentence.

722
00:41:34,005 --> 00:41:35,703
Well, if I was on James' jury,

723
00:41:35,828 --> 00:41:38,343
I'd be inclined to give him
a second chance.

724
00:41:39,370 --> 00:41:40,370
Here.

725
00:41:42,810 --> 00:41:44,810
- Would you like some more good news?
- Yeah?

726
00:41:44,935 --> 00:41:46,837
- You got the loan?
- 7 figures.

727
00:41:47,659 --> 00:41:50,329
It'll keep us afloat for at least
a year, long enough to get us

728
00:41:51,101 --> 00:41:53,512
- back on our feet.
- Congratulations.

729
00:41:54,269 --> 00:41:55,501
Well done, Foster.

730
00:41:55,626 --> 00:41:57,931
Thanks to Clara for getting us
in touch with the equity firm.

